"<b>Uncovenanted</b>, un-kuv′e-nan-ted, <i>adj.</i> not promised by covenant: not bound by a covenant, esp. not subscribing to the famous Solemn League and Covenant of 1643.—<b>Uncovenanted civil service</b>, a branch of the East Indian civil service whose members pass no entrance examination, and may resign their offices at pleasure—opp. to <i>Covenanted service</i>; <b>Uncovenanted mercies</b>, such mercies as God may bestow on those not embraced within the covenant of grace—that is, those outside the ordinary channels of grace.",
"<b>Uncover</b>, un-kuv′ėr, <i>v.t.</i> to remove the cover of: to lay open: to expose successively lines of formation of troops by the wheeling to right or left of the lines in front.—<i>v.i.</i> to take off the hat.—<i>adj.</i> <b>Uncov′ered</b>, having no covering, naked, esp. having no covering on the head.",
