"<b>Unkept</b>, un-kept′, <i>adj.</i> not kept or sustained.",
"<b>Unkind</b>, un-kīnd′, <i>adj.</i> contrary to kind or nature: wanting in kindness: cruel.—<i>n.</i> <b>Unkīnd′liness</b>, want of kindliness.—<i>adj.</i> <b>Unkīnd′ly</b>, contrary to kind or nature: malignant: not kind.—<i>adv.</i> (<i>Milt.</i>) in a manner contrary to kind or nature: in an unkindly manner: cruelly.—<i>n.</i> <b>Unkīnd′ness</b>, want of kindness or affection: cruelty.—<i>adj.</i> <b>Unkin′dred</b> (<i>obs.</i>), not related.—<i>adv.</i> <b>Unkin′dredly</b>.",
