"SYMBOLS USED IN MEDICINE AND PHARMACY.",
"<jsdocimg>000069.png</jsdocimg> Scruple; <jsdocimg>000069.png</jsdocimg>i, one scruple; <jsdocimg>000069.png</jsdocimg>ij, two scruples; <jsdocimg>000069.png</jsdocimg>ss, half a scruple; <jsdocimg>000069.png</jsdocimg>iss, a scruple and a half.",
"<jsdocimg>000075.png</jsdocimg> Dram or drachm; <jsdocimg>000075.png</jsdocimg>i, one dram; <jsdocimg>000075.png</jsdocimg>ij, two drams; <jsdocimg>000075.png</jsdocimg>ss, half a dram; <jsdocimg>000075.png</jsdocimg>iss, a dram and a half.",
"<jsdocimg>000081.png</jsdocimg> Ounce; <jsdocimg>000081.png</jsdocimg>i, one ounce; <jsdocimg>000081.png</jsdocimg>ij, two ounces; <jsdocimg>000081.png</jsdocimg>ss, half an ounce; <jsdocimg>000081.png</jsdocimg>iss, an ounce and a half.",
"<jsdocimg>000087.png</jsdocimg> A minim; a drop.",
"<jsdocimg>000093.png</jsdocimg> (Gr. <i>ana</i>), of each a like quantity.",
"<jsdocimg>000099.png</jsdocimg> (L. <i>recipe</i>), take.",
"The above symbols are employed almost always in medical prescriptions. A prescription consists of the following parts: (1) The <i>Superscription</i>; (2) The <i>Inscription</i>; (3) The <i>Subscription</i>; (4) The <i>Signature</i>. The <i>Superscription</i>, which consists of the letter <jsdocimg>000099.png</jsdocimg>, is a relic of the days of astrology. It originally was used to represent the symbol of the planet Jupiter. By common consent it is now regarded as representing the imperative mood of the Latin verb <i>recipere</i>, to take. The <i>Inscription</i> is a statement of the names of the substances to be used, with their quantities. The <i>Subscription</i> is made up of the directions for the guidance of the dispenser. The <i>Signature</i> includes the directions to the patient. This part of the prescription should be written in English; the other parts are in Latin. Sometimes the signature also is in Latin.",
"The body or prescription contains the following: the <i>Basis</i>, or principal active ingredient; the <i>Adjuvant</i>, or <i>Auxiliary</i>, to assist its action; the <i>Corrective</i>, to correct or diminish some undesirable quality; the <i>Vehicle</i>, or <i>Excipient</i>, to give a suitable form for administration.",
